  "case_id": "D2N072",
  "method": "direct",
  "template": "sectioned",
  "summary_text": "Chief Complaint\nRight finger pain.\n\nHistory of Present Illness\nThe patient reports right finger pain following a skiing injury over the weekend, sustained while skiing moguls. He describes getting his strap caught on his finger, resulting in a bend of the finger. He has been applying ice and taking ibuprofen, but the pain persists. He reports constipation recently and takes miralax.\n\nFindings\nExamination reveals tenderness over the distal phalanx of the right index finger and the distal interphalangeal joint. Range of motion is limited with flexion. Radiographs demonstrate no fractures.\n\nAssessment\nRight hand index finger contusion.\n\nPlan\nPrescribe an aluminum foam splint and order ibuprofen 600 milligrams every six hours for one week. Schedule follow-up if symptoms do not improve.",
  "reference_summary": "CC:\n\nRight finger pain.\n\nHPI:\n\nMs. Brooks is a 48-year-old female who presents today for an evaluation of right finger pain. She states she was skiing on Sunday and hyperextended her finger when it became caught in a strap on a jump. She has tried applying ice and taking Ibuprofen, but it is still very painful. She has pain with movement.\n\nCURRENT MEDICATIONS:\n\nMiraLax\n\nPAST MEDICAL HISTORY:\n\nConstipation.\n\nPAST SURGICAL HISTORY:\n\nAppendectomy.\n\nEXAM\n\nExamination of the right index finger shows tenderness over the distal phalanx. No tenderness over the proximal phalanx or the MP joint. Pain with flexion.\n\nRESULTS\n\nX-rays of the right hand show no obvious signs of fracture or bony abnormalities.\n\nIMPRESSION\n\nRight hand index finger contusion at the tip of the finger.\n\nPLAN\n\nAt this point, I discussed the diagnosis and treatment options with the patient. I have recommended a splint. She will take Motrin 600 mg every 6 hours for a week. If she does not improve, she will follow up with me. All questions were answered.",
